name: n-(p-aminobenzoyl)glutamic acid
Reason: The compound n-(p-aminobenzoyl)glutamic acid contains several functional groups that affect its melting point. The basic structure is glutamic acid, an amino acid, which has a melting point around 200°C. The addition of the p-aminobenzoyl group adds both an aromatic ring and an additional amide bond. Aromatic rings tend to increase the melting point due to their rigid planar structure and ability to stack well in the solid state, which can be estimated as a +20°C increase. The amide bond can form intermolecular hydrogen bonds, which typically increase the melting point further; this could be estimated as a +30°C increase. However, the added amino group on the benzoyl ring could introduce additional hydrogen bonding, but as it is an amino group substituted on an aromatic ring, its hydrogen-bonding ability might be less pronounced compared to aliphatic amines. Therefore, it might contribute a smaller increase in melting point, say around +10°C. Overall, the additional molecular weight and polar functional groups increase the melting point, while the increased molecular complexity with potential internal hydrogen bonding could lower it slightly compared to the base molecule glutamic acid.
